    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary containing: total row count, minimum timestamp, maximum timestamp, list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to 100), and list of unique KPI/feature names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name; limit each list to 100). Additionally for error_logs.csv return up to 10 sample rows with columns (timestamp, cmdb_id, message). Do not print full datasets. Keep output concise and structured."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we obtained file-level summaries: metric.csv contains 319,703 rows covering 2022-03-20 11:30→12:30 (UTC+8) with 59 cmdb_id and 1,368 kpi_name; trace.csv and log.csv cover 12:00→12:30 (UTC+8). error_logs.csv is empty. Next we should use metrics to narrow candidate components/time ranges by computing global thresholds (P95) per component-KPI using the full available series, then detect anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 — 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08). This step will produce a compact ranked list of metric-based anomaly candidates to focus trace/log analysis on. No detailed metric time series should be printed, only aggregated anomaly summary per component-KPI (top candidates).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following in code: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 of 'value' using the full series in metric.csv (do NOT filter yet). 2) Filter metric.csv rows to the incident window: timestamps between 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 and 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08 inclusive (Executor will convert to epoch seconds). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count = number of rows in the window where value >= global_P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum timestamp among those rows), max_value_in_window, and global_P95. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 component-KPIs sorted by anomaly_count descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_P95. Also return the total number of distinct component-KPIs scanned. Keep outputs limited to these aggregates; store full intermediate results in kernel variables but do not print them."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metric-level anomaly summary for the incident window and found the top component-KPIs by anomaly_count. However, the top entries are dominated by constant or monotonic metrics (container start times, node disk total, JVM start times, committed virtual memory) that naturally equal their global P95 and therefore are false-positive candidates for runtime faults. These do not indicate resource spikes or transient faults. We must exclude such constant/metadata KPIs and re-rank metric anomalies by actual severity (relative breach above global P95) to surface real faults (CPU, memory usage, disk IO, network, error counts, latency-related KPIs). The next step is to scan metric.csv again (global P95 computed from full series) but exclude KPI names containing common constant/metadata patterns (e.g., 'StartTime', 'container_start_time', 'system.disk.total', 'Runtime_StartTime', 'LastGcInfo') and compute a severity ratio = (max_in_window - global_P95)/global_P95 for those component-KPIs that have anomalies in the window. Return a compact top list of up to 30 candidates sorted by severity_ratio descending (and include anomaly_count and earliest anomaly timestamp).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv do the following in code: 1) Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (no filtering). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 → 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08. 3) Exclude any kpi_name that contains any of these substrings (case-sensitive): 'StartTime', 'container_start_time', 'system.disk.total', 'Runtime_StartTime', 'LastGcInfo'. 4) For each remaining (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count = count of rows in window where value >= global_P95; earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among those rows); max_value_in_window; global_P95; severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_P95)/global_P95 (use safe denom to avoid div-by-zero). 5) Return a compact table of top 30 rows where anomaly_count>0, sorted by severity_ratio descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_P95, severity_ratio. Also return the total number of distinct component-KPIs scanned after exclusion. Limit displayed rows to 30."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have run metric, trace, and log scans for the incident window (2022-03-20 12:00→12:30 UTC+8). Key findings so far:\n- Metric analysis (after excluding constant metadata KPIs) surfaced many anomalies starting at timestamp 1647748800 (2022-03-20 12:00:00+08). The prominent metric signals are container I/O (container_fs_reads/writes on /dev/vda) and container_memory_failures concentrated on containers scheduled on node-6 (and some on node-5). Many of these KPIs have global_P95 == 0, so severity ratios are inflated; nevertheless, the anomalies are widespread and start at 12:00.\n- Trace analysis shows many high anomalies (duration/error_rate) and some low traffic (row_count) anomalies beginning at the same timestamp 1647748800. Affected trace sources include frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0 and checkoutservice-2; checkoutservice-2 has a notable low row_count to currencyservice-2 (traffic drop). This pattern suggests degraded request handling starting at 12:00 that affected many downstream calls.\n- Log analysis returns many log.error_count anomalies with global_P95 == 0 (likely false positives due to sparsity) and a notable log.row_count anomaly for recommendationservice-2 (large traffic swing) starting at 12:00. error_logs.csv is empty.\nInterpretation so far: A broad I/O / container memory-failure signal anchored on node-6 (and some node-5) coincides with widespread trace degradations starting exactly at 12:00:00+08. This suggests at least one node-level failure (likely node-6 affecting many containers) beginning at 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08. There is also a service-level traffic drop to currencyservice-2 observed from checkoutservice-2 traces; this could be a second, service-specific failure or part of the same node-level failure affecting currencyservice instances. We need to confirm node attribution and list affected containers to determine whether there are two separate root-cause incidents (multiple nodes or one node + one service). Next step: aggregate and quantify container I/O and memory-failure anomalies per node (count of affected KPIs/containers, earliest anomaly timestamp, example affected containers) to confirm which node(s) are the predominant source of metric anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, perform this focused analysis: 1) Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full metric series (no filtering). 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 → 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08. 3) Select metric rows whose kpi_name contains any of: 'container_fs_reads', 'container_fs_writes', 'container_fs_reads_MB', 'container_fs_writes_MB', or 'container_memory_failures'. 4) For each selected row determine if it is an anomaly: value >= global_P95 (use safe comparison). 5) Aggregate anomalies by node identifier extracted from kpi_name pattern 'container.node-N' or from cmdb_id if node-level (map container kpis to their node using the substring 'container.node-<N>' inside kpi_name). For each node compute: node_id (e.g., node-6), total_anomaly_count (sum of anomalous rows), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp of anomalous rows), number_of_affected_containers (count distinct cmdb_id among anomalous rows), and top_affected_containers (list up to 10 distinct cmdb_id sorted by their anomaly counts). 6) Return a compact table of nodes sorted by total_anomaly_count desc (limit to top 10) with the fields above. Keep outputs compact; store full intermediate tables in kernel variables but do not print them."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metrics, traces, and logs for 2022-03-20 12:00–12:30 (UTC+8). Key derived facts:\n- Metric I/O/memory-failure KPIs (container_fs_reads/writes and container_memory_failures) concentrate on node-6 (total_anomaly_count=11588, earliest=1647748800 → 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08) and secondarily node-5 (1762 anomalies, earliest=12:00:00+08). Node-6 affects many containers (34 distinct cmdb_id). This strongly indicates a node-level problem beginning at 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 — likely node-6 experiencing I/O pressure and container memory failures.\n- Trace analysis shows widespread duration/error_rate spikes and some traffic drops starting at the same timestamp 1647748800. checkoutservice-2 shows both high duration/error_rate and a low row_count to currencyservice-2 (row_count anomaly_count=30), indicating reduced traffic or failures calling currencyservice-2.\n- Log analysis is noisy: many log.error_count anomalies have global_P95==0 (sparsity artifact). A notable log.row_count anomaly exists for recommendationservice-2, but logs do not give clear textual errors (error_logs.csv is empty).\nConclusion so far: there is a strong node-level failure on node-6 starting at 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 that explains the broad service degradations. There is also a service-specific symptom for currencyservice-2 (traffic drop) at the same time; to decide whether this is a second independent failure or a consequence of node-6, we must confirm whether currencyservice-2 was running on node-6 and whether its container-level metrics show I/O or memory-failure anomalies. If currencyservice-2 runs on node-6 and shows the same metric anomalies, the incident is likely a single root cause (node-6). If currencyservice-2 runs elsewhere and shows isolated anomalies, it may represent a second failure. We need to inspect currencyservice-2 metrics (container-level KPIs and their node mapping) in the incident window (global thresholds computed from full series) to confirm.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, focus on cmdb_id 'currencyservice-2': 1) Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) from the full series (do NOT filter). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 → 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08. 3) From the filtered rows select KPIs whose names contain any of: 'container.node-', 'container_fs_reads', 'container_fs_writes', 'container_fs_reads_MB', 'container_fs_writes_MB', or 'container_memory_failures'. 4) For each selected (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count = count rows in window with value >= global_P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp among anomalous rows), max_value_in_window, global_P95, and extract node_id from the kpi_name substring 'container.node-<N>' if present (otherwise node_id = unknown). 5) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, node_id, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_P95. If no rows match, return an explicit empty result indicator."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step attempted to detect container I/O and memory-failure anomalies for currencyservice-2 inside the 12:00–12:30 window. The cell executed without printed output, which likely means either (a) no matching KPIs for currencyservice-2 were found among the selected KPI name patterns in the incident window, or (b) matching KPIs exist but none had anomalies (value >= global P95) in the window, or (c) the result was assigned to a variable but not displayed. From earlier aggregated results we know node-6 is the dominant source of I/O/memory-failure signals and checkoutservice-2 showed a traffic drop to currencyservice-2 at 12:00:00+08. To decide whether the currencyservice-2 traffic drop is a second independent failure or a symptom of the node-6 problem, we must confirm on which node(s) currencyservice-2 runs and whether its container-level I/O or memory-failure KPIs show anomalies in the window. This will tell us if currencyservice-2 containers were affected by node-6 issues (supporting a single node-level root cause) or whether currencyservice-2 has isolated faults (supporting a second failure).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan metric.csv (full series) for currencyservice-2 and report a compact mapping and anomaly summary: \n1) From the full metric.csv (no time filtering), find all kpi_name values for cmdb_id == 'currencyservice-2' that contain the substring 'container.node-<N>' and extract the distinct node_id(s) (format node-<N>). Return the list of unique node_id values and counts of how many distinct kpi_names map to each node_id (limit to top 10). \n2) Also from the full series compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) for those currencyservice-2 KPIs whose kpi_name contains any of these substrings: 'container_fs_reads', 'container_fs_writes', 'container_fs_reads_MB', 'container_fs_writes_MB', 'container_memory_failures'. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, node_id (extracted), global_P95. \n3) Now filter metric.csv to the incident window 2022-03-20 12:00:00+08 → 2022-03-20 12:30:00+08 and for the same selected KPIs compute anomaly_count = number of rows in the window with value >= global_P95. Return for each KPI (limit 20 rows) the columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, node_id, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (if anomaly_count>0), max_value_in_window, global_P95. \nKeep outputs compact (top rows only), and explicitly indicate if no matching KPIs or no anomalies were found."
}

